nal-plugins\",\"slug\":\"delegated-hugging-cherny\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T09:14:57.621Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01H9afGL881fQcG3skpsAdQ4\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_015YkEoyRohmZaPMQL6XqfT4\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/nodo/work/cli/docs/requirements/external-plugins/review-01.md\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":247,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":84104,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":247},\"output_tokens\":25,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYjgLAPcVet6iE73C3fGx\",\"uuid\":\"8457ca4d-7ec4-468c-8c2a-cc20429a715f\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"acf8d786c4bdadd9e\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_012DXLQTpm4TaVJmo93oGb44\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01Y7S6hEkU5EgFjKc8gd89uT\",\"uuid\":\"7386c126-1710-4598-8d2c-fc40fe783970\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T09:14:57.622Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"7386c126-1710-4598-8d2c-fc40fe783970\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/nodo/work/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"dccb059e-a37d-4287-9fa3-471a6aa16f44\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"nodo/external-plugins\",\"slug\":\"delegated-hugging-cherny\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_015YkEoyRohmZaPMQL6XqfT4\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Review 01\\n     2→\\n     3→> Status: pending-dev\\n     4→> Date: 2026-03-04\\n     5→> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n     6→> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n     7→\\n     8→## Previous Review Status\\n     9→\\n    10→No previous reviews.\\n    11→\\n    12→## New Findings\\n    13→\\n    14→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    15→\\n    16→1. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:211] Unbounded `io.ReadAll` on stdin in `ParseHookEvent`**\\n    17→\\n    18→   `ParseHookEvent` calls `io.ReadAll(stdin)` without any size limit. Since external plugins receive data from agent hooks (which may include arbitrary payloads), a malformed or malicious input stream could cause OOM. This is especially important because `ParseHookEvent` is called during git hook execution, where the CLI acts as a gatekeeper.\\n    19→\\n    20→   Suggested fix: Use `io.LimitReader(stdin, maxParseHookBytes)` with a reasonable limit (e.g., 10MB).\\n    21→\\n    22→   ```go\\n    23→   const maxParseHookBytes = 10 * 1024 * 1024\\n    24→   data, err := io.ReadAll(io.LimitReader(stdin, maxParseHookBytes))\\n    25→   ```\\n    26→\\n    27→2. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:97-98] `ReadTranscript` passes `sessionRef` as a CLI argument without validation**\\n    28→\\n    29→   The `sessionRef` value originates from session metadata and is passed as `--session-ref` to the external binary. In the test agent (`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire-agent-test/main.go`:167), this is used directly as a file path in `os.ReadFile(*sessionRef)`. While the CLI itself is not performing the file read, it is passing potentially attacker-controlled strings to an external process as arguments.\\n    30→\\n    31→   This is less of a concern than it might appear because:\\n    32→   - The external binary is trusted (found on PATH, user opted in via `external_agents: true`)\\n    33→   - The CLI is not interpreting the value, just forwarding it\\n    34→\\n    35→   However, the `sessionRef` and similar path parameters (`--path`, `--session-dir`, `--subagents-dir`) are passed as CLI arguments that could contain shell metacharacters. Since `exec.CommandContext` does NOT invoke a shell, this is safe from shell injection. **No action required** -- documenting this for the record.\\n    36→\\n    37→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    38→\\n    39→3. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:97-98, 118, 128, 140, 152, 169, 193, 272, 284, 297, 310, 334, 363, 373, 386] Many methods use `context.Background()` instead of accepting a context parameter**\\n    40→\\n    41→   Fifteen methods create a fresh `context.Background()` instead of propagating a caller-supplied context. This means:\\n    42→   - The 30-second default timeout from `run()` is the only safeguard\\n    43→   - Callers cannot cancel these operations (e.g., during graceful shutdown)\\n    44→   - Operations triggered during git hooks (which have tight time budgets) cannot enforce their own deadlines\\n    45→\\n    46→   The `agent.Agent` interface methods like `ReadTranscript`, `GetSessionID`, `ResolveSessionFile`, `FormatResumeCommand`, etc. do not accept a context, so fixing this would require interface changes. At minimum, consider:\\n    47→   - Filing a follow-up issue to add context to the agent interface\\n    48→   - Adding a comment explaining why `context.Background()` is used (interface limitation)\\n    49→\\n    50→4. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go`:31-32] Discovery timeout context is cancelled immediately after `DiscoverAndRegister` returns, but the context was already used synchronously**\\n    51→\\n    52→   The code is:\\n    53→   ```go\\n    54→   discoveryCtx, discoveryCancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 5*time.Second)\\n    55→   defer discoveryCancel()\\n    56→   external.DiscoverAndRegister(discoveryCtx)\\n    57→   ```\\n    58→\\n    59→   The `defer discoveryCancel()` fires when `newHooksCmd()` returns. Since `DiscoverAndRegister` is synchronous, this works correctly. However, there is a subtle issue: the 5-second timeout is for ALL discovery combined. If there are many `entire-agent-*` binaries on PATH, each `New()` call gets a share of this budget, but a single slow binary could consume most of it, starving later ones. The `New()` call inherits the discovery context deadline, so slow binaries will eventually timeout, but the remaining budget for subsequent binaries shrinks.\\n    60→\\n    61→   This is acceptable for now but worth documenting. Consider logging the remaining budget when starting each binary probe during discovery.\\n    62→\\n    63→5. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go`:55-56] Agent name from filename is used without sanitization**\\n    64→\\n    65→   The agent name is derived from the binary filename:\\n    66→   ```go\\n    67→   agentName := types.AgentName(strings.TrimPrefix(name, binaryPrefix))\\n    68→   ```\\n    69→\\n    70→   If a binary is named `entire-agent-../../etc/shadow`, the resulting agent name would be `../../etc/shadow`. While this does not cause path traversal (the name is used as a registry key, not a file path), it could cause confusion in logs and display. Consider validating the agent name contains only `[a-z0-9-]` characters.\\n    71→\\n    72→   Suggested fix:\\n    73→   ```go\\n    74→   agentName := strings.TrimPrefix(name, binaryPrefix)\\n    75→   if !regexp.MustCompile(`^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9-]*$`).MatchString(agentName) {\\n    76→       logging.Debug(ctx, \\\"skipping external agent (invalid name)\\\", slog.String(\\\"binary\\\", name))\\n    77→       continue\\n    78→   }\\n    79→   ```\\n    80→\\n    81→6. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:415-416] `cmd.Environ()` inherits the full parent environment**\\n    82→\\n    83→   The external binary receives the entire environment of the CLI process. This includes potentially sensitive variables (API keys, tokens, etc.). Consider using a minimal environment instead, or at least documenting this as a security consideration in the protocol docs.\\n    84→\\n    85→   At minimum, the protocol documentation should state that external agents receive the parent process environment, so plugin authors are aware they should not leak env vars.\\n    86→\\n    87→7. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:427] No limit on stdout buffer size**\\n    88→\\n    89→   `cmd.Stdout = &stdoutBuf` collects the entire stdout of the external binary into memory. A malicious or buggy external agent could write gigabytes to stdout, causing OOM. Consider wrapping the buffer with a `LimitedWriter` or checking the size after the process exits.\\n    90→\\n    91→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n    92→\\n    93→8. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external_test.go`:36-101] Test mock scripts use shell string interpolation for JSON**\\n    94→\\n    95→   The `mockInfoScript` function builds shell scripts by string-concatenating JSON:\\n    96→   ```go\\n    97→   return `#!/bin/sh\\n    98→   case \\\"$1\\\" in\\n    99→     info)\\n   100→       echo '` + infoJSON + `'\\n   101→   ```\\n   102→\\n   103→   If `infoJSON` contains single quotes, this will break the shell script. The current tests are safe because the JSON values are controlled, but this is fragile. Consider using a heredoc or writing the JSON to a separate file that the script reads.\\n   104→\\n   105→9. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/capabilities.go`] `wrappedAgent` duplicates every method signature from `Agent`**\\n   106→\\n   107→   The `wrappedAgent` is a thin delegation layer with ~80 lines of boilerplate. This is a reasonable approach in Go (no built-in delegation), but consider adding a comment at the top of the struct explaining why all methods are forwarded rather than using embedding (embedding would expose the underlying `*Agent` directly and bypass capability gating).\\n   108→\\n   109→10. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go`:22-93] `DiscoverAndRegister` has no way to report partial failures to callers**\\n   110→\\n   111→    All errors during discovery are logged and swallowed. The function returns nothing. This is fine for the current fire-and-forget usage, but if callers ever need to know which agents failed and why (e.g., for `entire status` diagnostics), the function signature would need to change.\\n   112→\\n   113→    Consider returning a `[]DiscoveryError` or similar for future extensibility, even if current callers ignore it.\\n   114→\\n   115→11. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/types.go`:148-172] `eventJSON.toEvent()` uses unchecked integer cast for `EventType`**\\n   116→\\n   117→    ```go\\n   118→    ev := &agent.Event{\\n   119→        Type: agent.EventType(ej.Type),\\n   120→    ```\\n   121→\\n   122→    The `ej.Type` integer is directly cast to `agent.EventType` without validating it is a known event type. An external agent returning an unknown event type (e.g., `999`) would propagate through the system. Consider validating the type against known values.\\n   123→\\n   124→12. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:123-137] `GetSessionID` silently returns empty string on any error**\\n   125→\\n   126→    Three different error paths (marshal, run, unmarshal) all return `\\\"\\\"`. This matches the interface contract (built-in agents also return `\\\"\\\"` on failure), but makes debugging difficult. Consider adding debug logging for these failures:\\n   127→\\n   128→    ```go\\n   129→    func (e *Agent) GetSessionID(input *agent.HookInput) string {\\n   130→        data, err := marshalHookInput(input)\\n   131→        if err != nil {\\n   132→            logging.Debug(context.Background(), \\\"GetSessionID marshal failed\\\", slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n   133→            return \\\"\\\"\\n   134→        }\\n   135→        // ...\\n   136→    }\\n   137→    ```\\n   138→\\n   139→13. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go`:31-33] Discovery runs on every `entire hooks` invocation**\\n   140→\\n   141→    `DiscoverAndRegister` scans PATH and calls `info` on every matching binary, which happens on every git hook invocation (commit, push, etc.). This adds latency to every git operation. The 5-second timeout bounds worst case, but even the happy path involves filesystem scanning + process spawning for each plugin.\\n   142→\\n   143→    Consider caching discovery results (e.g., in a temp file with a short TTL) to avoid re-scanning on every hook call. This is especially important because git hooks are latency-sensitive.\\n   144→\\n   145→### Praise\\n   146→\\n   147→- **Capability gating pattern (`capabilities.go`)**: The `CapabilityDeclarer` + `As*` helper pattern is elegant. It allows external agents to implement all interfaces (through the `wrappedAgent`) while only exposing declared capabilities, AND it preserves backward compatibility with built-in agents that use direct type assertions. This is a well-thought-out design.\\n   148→\\n   149→- **Thorough test coverage**: The test suite covers happy paths, error cases, deduplication, name conflicts, non-executable files, directories, disabled settings, empty PATH, unreadable directories, and info failures. The capability gating tests cover all combinations of declared/undeclared capabilities for every optional interface.\\n   150→\\n   151→- **Security-conscious defaults**: The feature flag (`external_agents: false` by default), the 5-second discovery timeout, the 30-second per-call timeout, and the `WaitDelay` on subprocesses all show good defensive thinking.\\n   152→\\n   153→- **Clean refactoring**: The migration from direct type assertions (`ag.(agent.HookSupport)`) to the capability-aware helpers (`agent.AsHookSupport(ag)`) across the codebase is thorough and consistent, touching all 15+ call sites without missing any.\\n   154→\\n   155→- **Protocol versioning**: Including `protocol_version` in the `info` response and checking it upfront prevents subtle compatibility issues as the protocol evolves.\\n   156→\\n   157→## Summary\\n   158→\\n   159→**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n   160→\\n   161→The architecture is sound and the implementation is well-structured. The capability gating pattern is particularly nice. However, there are security concerns that should be addressed before merging since this feature executes untrusted external binaries:\\n   162→\\n   163→**Key concerns:**\\n   164→1. Unbounded `io.ReadAll` in `ParseHookEvent` (item 1) -- a straightforward fix\\n   165→2. No stdout size limit from external processes (item 7) -- could cause OOM\\n   166→3. Agent name from filename not validated (item 5) -- low risk but easy fix\\n   167→4. Discovery latency on every git hook invocation (item 13) -- may impact user experience\\n   168→\\n   169→**Estimated effort to address feedback:**\\n   170→- Critical + Important fixes: ~2-3 hours\\n   171→- Suggestions: ~1-2 hours (optional, can be follow-up)\\n   172→\\n   173→All tests pass. The code is well-organized and follows the project's conventions.\\n   174→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"e6b3d9aa-cc19-4a2d-82cb-41dabd479d06\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T09:14:57.659Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"acf8d786c4bdadd9e\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_012DXLQTpm4TaVJmo93oGb44\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01Y7S6hEkU5EgFjKc8gd89uT\",\"uuid\":\"e5765c30-dc5d-4152-8fbe-633dfa0fe6f8\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T09:14:57.660Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"e5765c30-dc5d-4152-8fbe-633dfa0fe6f8\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/nodo/work/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"dccb059e-a37d-4287-9fa3-471a6aa16f44\",\"version\":\"2.1.69\",\"gitBranch\":\"nodo/external-plugins\",\"slug\":\"delegated-hugging-cherny\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T09:15:01.801Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01Stv94GkQ6iHJ4RgXvcoZBL\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_us